article.description: Tamika Catchings scored four of her 17 points in the final 14 seconds to lead the Indiana Fever to a 72-68 victory at New York on Friday night, snapping the Liberty's six-game winning streak.
article.headline: Catchings catches fire for Fever
article.linkText: Indiana snaps New York's six-game win streak
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Two days after squandering a big first-half lead
against the defending WNBA champions, the Indiana Fever provided
their own comeback against the league-leading New York Liberty.

Tamika Catchings scored four of her 17 points in the final 14
seconds to lead Indiana to a 72-68 victory at New York, as the
Fever rallied from a 13-point deficit in the second half.

"At halftime we talked about cutting the lead in half in the
first five to seven minutes," Fever coach Brian Winters said. "We
got the lead down to a manageable level and it was anybody's
game."

After Catchings' driving layup with 13.9 seconds left gave
Indiana a 70-65 lead, Crystal Robinson hit a 3-pointer with 7.5
seconds remaining to cut New York's deficit to two points.
Catchings then hit a pair of free throws with 4.7 seconds left to
seal Indiana's win.

The Fever snapped the Liberty's six-game winning streak, and
beat them for the third straight time -- handing New York both its
losses this season. Indiana has won five of the last six meetings
with the Liberty.

Deanna Jackson and Kelly Miller added 13 points apiece, and
Natalie Williams had 10 points and 10 rebounds for the Fever.

Indiana was coming off an 83-79 loss at home to Detroit on
Wednesday, after the Fever scored a franchise-record 51 points in
the first half to take a 19-point lead.

Becky Hammon had 22 points and Crystal Robinson added 14 to lead
the Liberty, who lost for the first time since dropping the season
opener at Indiana -- 69-67 on May 21.

"The Liberty are a great team," Catchings said. "It's just
great to come off with a win tonight."

New York led 44-32 at halftime, and stretched its lead to 13 on
Tari Phillips' free throw 27 seconds into the second half.

However, Indiana then scored nine straight points and cut the
deficit to four on Miller's 10-foot jumper with 16:26 remaining.
The Fever took the lead at 52-51 on Kelly Schumacher's hook shot
with 9:05 left.

Elena Baranova's 3-pointer cut the Liberty's deficit to 59-57
five minutes later, before Schumacher responded with her own 3 with
3:37 left to restore Indiana's five-point lead.

"Tamika Catchings is 70 percent of their offense, but they had
some other players step up tonight," New York coach Richie Adubato
said. "Schumacher hit that big 3-point shot. She's been hitting
that shot consistently for them."

After shooting 61 percent (17-for-28) from the field in the
first half, New York was just 21 percent (6-for-29) in the second
half.

"We came out in the second half and our defense was really
solid," Winters said. "They missed some shots and we took away
some of their 3-point attempts to get back in the game."

Hammon scored 15 points in the first half on 5-for-7 shooting,
including 3-for-4 on 3-pointers. However, with Catchings guarding
her most of the second half, Hammon made just 2 of 9 shots after
the break.

"We just knew we had to pick it up defensively," Catchings
said. "If that meant I had to guard someone different, then I was
willing to do that. In the first half, they were getting shots
whenever they wanted to, and that sparked them."

Catchings hit a pair of free throws to give the Fever their
biggest lead of the game at 64-58.

The Fever shot 41.7 percent from the field against a Liberty
team that was allowing a league-low 37-percent shooting.
